The second question will provide us with examples

34
00:01:31,710 --> 00:01:33,880
that govern what the allowable laws of physics are.

35
00:01:35,040 --> 00:01:35,520
Okay,

36
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:37,840
so I like to start,

37
00:01:37,840 --> 00:01:39,720
and I always do in these classes,

38
00:01:39,720 --> 00:01:42,760
with a very simple set of illustrations.

39
00:01:43,660 --> 00:01:45,860
Who can guess what my illustrations are going to be?

40
00:01:48,340 --> 00:01:48,820
Coins,

41
00:01:48,820 --> 00:01:49,120
right?

42
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:50,380
Right,

43
00:01:50,380 --> 00:01:50,820
of course.

44
00:01:51,300 --> 00:01:52,580
That's because you've been here before.

45
00:01:54,840 --> 00:01:55,320
Coins.

46
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:56,890
Let's take the very simplest

47
00:01:56,890 --> 00:01:58,380
system that I can think of.

48
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:00,400
A coin.

49
00:02:00,680 --> 00:02:01,960
I don't have a coin.

50
00:02:02,140 --> 00:02:02,520
I...

51
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:05,020
So,

52
00:02:05,020 --> 00:02:06,300
when I say a coin,

53
00:02:06,300 --> 00:02:08,740
I mean an abstract coin

54
00:02:08,740 --> 00:02:11,180
laid down on an abstract table.

55
00:02:11,440 --> 00:02:13,450
The only thing about the coin which is

56
00:02:13,450 --> 00:02:15,460
relevant to us is whether it's heads or tails.

57
00:02:16,140 --> 00:02:17,900
The coin has two states.

58
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:19,060
Two states of being,

59
00:02:19,060 --> 00:02:20,500
two configurations,

60
00:02:20,500 --> 00:02:23,500
two values,

61
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:24,900
however we want to call it.

62
00:02:25,160 --> 00:02:26,940
Heads or tails.

63
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:29,040
So there are two states.

64
00:02:29,140 --> 00:02:29,520
This is our first step.

65
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:30,300
This is our dynamical system.

66
00:02:30,460 --> 00:02:31,120
It's one coin,

67
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:33,200
and it has two states,

68
00:02:33,200 --> 00:02:35,240
heads or tails.

69
00:02:36,120 --> 00:02:37,580
That's all there is to the world,

70
00:02:37,580 --> 00:02:39,400
to this very simplified world.

71
00:02:40,740 --> 00:02:41,180
Question?

72
00:02:42,280 --> 00:02:42,860
Of course,

73
00:02:42,860 --> 00:02:44,120
there's an even simpler world.

74
00:02:44,280 --> 00:02:46,080
We can even go back to a simpler world.

75
00:02:46,340 --> 00:02:48,400
It's a coin with only one side.

76
00:02:49,620 --> 00:02:51,080
Then it's even simpler.

77
00:02:51,300 --> 00:02:53,920
All it can be is that one state.

78
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:55,480
That's a little too simple.

79
00:02:55,840 --> 00:02:56,860
Nothing can happen.

80
00:02:56,960 --> 00:02:57,920
Nothing ever happens.

81
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:00,840
So,

82
00:03:00,840 --> 00:03:02,240
this is our world.

83
00:03:02,480 --> 00:03:04,460
What is an initial condition?

84
00:03:04,940 --> 00:03:08,520
An initial condition is it's either heads or tails.

85
00:03:09,560 --> 00:03:10,120
Now,

86
00:03:10,120 --> 00:03:11,800
what about laws of motion?

87
00:03:12,440 --> 00:03:14,660
Now we're going to make up some laws of motion.

88
00:03:14,820 --> 00:03:15,620
The laws of motion,

89
00:03:15,620 --> 00:03:16,680
of course,

90
00:03:16,680 --> 00:03:18,620
for this coin that just sits here,

91
00:03:18,620 --> 00:03:20,280
the law of motion is very,

92
00:03:20,280 --> 00:03:21,160
very simple.

93
00:03:22,480 --> 00:03:25,180
Let's put two circles here.

94
00:03:25,240 --> 00:03:26,300
One stands for heads,

95
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:27,740
and one stands for tails.

96
00:03:31,420 --> 00:03:33,590
What is the law of motion of

97
00:03:33,590 --> 00:03:35,760
this particular coin sitting on this particular table?

98
00:03:36,100 --> 00:03:39,580
The answer is it stays the same.

99
00:03:40,060 --> 00:03:40,660
So,

100
00:03:40,660 --> 00:03:42,550
if we imagine breaking up

101
00:03:42,550 --> 00:03:44,440
time into little successive intervals,

102
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:49,060
this stroboscopic world of a discrete coin like that,

103
00:03:49,280 --> 00:03:51,640
then the only thing that happens is nothing happens.

104
00:03:51,900 --> 00:03:53,040
Heads goes to heads.

105
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:57,120
Tails goes to tails.

106
00:03:58,680 --> 00:04:00,180
Or we can draw a picture.

107
00:04:01,100 --> 00:04:02,340
Heads goes to heads.

108
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:04,780
Starting with heads,

109
00:04:04,780 --> 00:04:06,140
we go back to heads.

110
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:07,740
Tails goes to tails.

111
00:04:08,280 --> 00:04:10,600
That's really a very boring law of physics,

112
00:04:10,600 --> 00:04:12,360
but it's a very powerful law

113
00:04:12,360 --> 00:04:14,120
of physics in that it tells you,

114
00:04:14,120 --> 00:04:14,960
however you start,

115
00:04:15,220 --> 00:04:16,980
you know where you will be

116
00:04:16,980 --> 00:04:18,740
arbitrarily down the line in time.

117
00:04:19,060 --> 00:04:19,380
All right?

118
00:04:19,839 --> 00:04:21,100
If you start with heads,

119
00:04:21,100 --> 00:04:24,900
the history of the world will be heads,

120
00:04:24,900 --> 00:04:25,860
heads,

121
00:04:25,860 --> 00:04:26,840
heads,

122
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:27,100
heads.

123
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:29,180
Heads dot dot dot forever and ever.

124
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:32,400
So this law may be very boring,

125
00:04:32,400 --> 00:04:33,400
but it's very powerful.

126
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:35,440
Or if you start with tails,

127
00:04:35,440 --> 00:04:36,480
it's going to be tails,

128
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:36,780
tails,

129
00:04:36,780 --> 00:04:37,120
tails,

130
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:37,440
tails,

131
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:38,980
as far as the eye can see.

132
00:04:40,320 --> 00:04:44,040
So that's an example of a dynamical system with a law

133
00:04:44,040 --> 00:04:47,760
of motion where the law of motion is just an updating,

134
00:04:47,760 --> 00:04:49,480
but it's in this case very trivial.

135
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:52,690
There's only really one other law of

136
00:04:52,690 --> 00:04:54,880
motion that you can imagine for this system.

137
00:04:55,500 --> 00:04:56,460
And what is it?

138
00:04:56,460 --> 00:05:00,200
It is that whatever it is at one instant,

139
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:03,300
at the next instant of the stroboscopic light,

140
00:05:03,300 --> 00:05:04,320
it's the opposite.

141
00:05:04,860 --> 00:05:06,420
And the next instance is the opposite.

142
00:05:07,020 --> 00:05:08,280
We could write it this way.

143
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:11,320
Heads goes to tails.

144
00:05:13,060 --> 00:05:14,180
Tails goes to heads.

145
00:05:18,680 --> 00:05:20,480
And we could make a picture of it.

146
00:05:20,620 --> 00:05:25,560
We could picture this law of motion by,

147
00:05:25,560 --> 00:05:25,860
again,

148
00:05:25,860 --> 00:05:26,260
arrow.

149
00:05:26,900 --> 00:05:28,980
An arrow from head to tails,

150
00:05:28,980 --> 00:05:30,760
which says that if you start at heads,

151
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:32,130
the tail end of the arrow

152
00:05:32,130 --> 00:05:33,500
always means what you start with.

153
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:35,240
The head end of the

154
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:36,600
arrow means where you'll end up.

155
00:05:37,799 --> 00:05:42,060
And that would be this law of physics.

156
00:05:42,300 --> 00:05:43,040
Heads goes to tails.

157
00:05:43,140 --> 00:05:43,780
Tails goes to heads.

158
00:05:43,900 --> 00:05:44,620
Heads goes to tails.

159
00:05:45,200 --> 00:05:47,820
And the history now of the world

160
00:05:47,820 --> 00:05:50,440
would be if you start with heads,

161
00:05:50,440 --> 00:05:52,300
you then go to tails.

162
00:05:52,540 --> 00:05:53,320
Then you go to heads.

163
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:54,480
Then you go to tails.

164
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:55,740
Dot dot dot.

165
00:05:56,460 --> 00:05:58,300
But if you start with tails,

166
00:05:58,300 --> 00:05:59,600
you go to heads,

167
00:05:59,600 --> 00:06:00,160
tails,

168
00:06:00,160 --> 00:06:00,640
heads.

169
00:06:01,060 --> 00:06:02,480
Still pretty boring,

170
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:06,260
but a little more interesting than the original first law.

171
00:06:08,760 --> 00:06:11,320
We could write some mathematics for this.

172
00:06:11,400 --> 00:06:11,600
In fact,

173
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:13,080
we can write an equation of motion.

174
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:15,540
Let's invent a symbol,

175
00:06:15,540 --> 00:06:16,480
a variable,

176
00:06:16,480 --> 00:06:18,840
which takes two values.

177
00:06:19,900 --> 00:06:22,000
Let me call it sigma.

178
00:06:22,880 --> 00:06:24,320
Why do I call it sigma?

179
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:28,150
It's because sigma is a traditional

180
00:06:28,150 --> 00:06:31,220
variable associated with two-valuedness in physics.

181
00:06:31,320 --> 00:06:33,340
It has to do with the spin

182
00:06:33,340 --> 00:06:35,360
of the electron or spin of particles,

183
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:36,780
but we don't need to know about that now.

184
00:06:37,240 --> 00:06:41,200
Sigma is a variable that is either equal to 1,

185
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:42,460
let's say,

186
00:06:42,460 --> 00:06:43,500
or minus 1.

187
00:06:43,980 --> 00:06:45,480
1 for heads,

188
00:06:45,480 --> 00:06:47,180
minus 1 for tails.

189
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:48,340
All right?

190
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:50,400
So instead of calling this heads and tails,

191
00:06:50,400 --> 00:06:53,400
we can call it sigma equals 1.

192
00:06:54,580 --> 00:06:56,900
And sigma equals minus 1.

193
00:06:59,580 --> 00:07:00,380
All right?

194
00:07:00,380 --> 00:07:03,480
We now have the idea of a configuration space which

195
00:07:03,480 --> 00:07:06,580
is labeled by the two possible values of a certain variable.

196
00:07:07,180 --> 00:07:11,380
It's not as rich as the variables we will use,

197
00:07:11,380 --> 00:07:11,920
for example,

198
00:07:11,920 --> 00:07:13,160
positions of particles,

199
00:07:13,160 --> 00:07:14,460
values of fields,

200
00:07:14,460 --> 00:07:15,740
or all sorts of other things.

201
00:07:16,140 --> 00:07:17,100
But nevertheless,

202
00:07:17,100 --> 00:07:19,800
it's a mathematical symbol whose value tells

203
00:07:19,800 --> 00:07:22,500
you which of the configurations you're in.

204
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:23,660
All right,

205
00:07:23,660 --> 00:07:25,400
let's take this first law of physics.

206
00:07:25,560 --> 00:07:26,700
The first law of physics,

207
00:07:26,700 --> 00:07:29,060
not the first law of physics,

208
00:07:29,060 --> 00:07:30,980
the first law that I wrote down,

209
00:07:30,980 --> 00:07:32,780
the previous law,

210
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:34,150
that was heads goes to

211
00:07:34,150 --> 00:07:35,340
heads and tails goes to tails.

212
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:38,060
Let me write that in a mathematical form.

213
00:07:38,700 --> 00:07:39,160
Oh,

214
00:07:39,160 --> 00:07:40,820
let's call time t.

215
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:43,980
In an astroboscopic world,

216
00:07:43,980 --> 00:07:45,800
t is an integer.

217
00:07:47,039 --> 00:07:48,800
t is 0,

218
00:07:48,800 --> 00:07:49,260
1,

219
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:49,620
2,

220
00:07:49,620 --> 00:07:49,960
3.

221
00:07:50,020 --> 00:07:51,080
It can also be minus 1,

222
00:07:51,080 --> 00:07:51,680
minus 2,

223
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:52,320
minus 3.

224
00:07:52,500 --> 00:07:54,180
So in an astroboscopic world,

225
00:07:54,180 --> 00:07:55,520
time is discrete,

226
00:07:55,520 --> 00:07:58,320
and it takes on integer values.

227
00:07:58,820 --> 00:08:02,060
So let's see if we can write an

228
00:08:02,060 --> 00:08:05,300
equation for the most boring law in the world.

229
00:08:05,560 --> 00:08:07,590
What it says is that whatever

230
00:08:07,590 --> 00:08:09,620
sigma is at a given time,

231
00:08:09,620 --> 00:08:10,820
let's put that over here,

232
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,240
sigma at time t,

233
00:08:13,240 --> 00:08:15,500
at the next instant,

234
00:08:15,500 --> 00:08:16,480
t plus 1,

235
00:08:18,640 --> 00:08:20,440
it will be equal to whatever

236
00:08:20,440 --> 00:08:22,240
it was at the instant t.

237
00:08:22,820 --> 00:08:25,220
This is just a law that

238
00:08:25,220 --> 00:08:27,620
says that the coin doesn't flip.

239
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:28,600
It just stays the same.

240
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:30,500
Whatever it is at one time,

241
00:08:30,500 --> 00:08:32,159
it will be the same at the neighboring time,

242
00:08:32,159 --> 00:08:33,020
at the next time.

243
00:08:34,200 --> 00:08:35,820
So that's the simple law heads,

244
00:08:35,820 --> 00:08:36,080
heads,

245
00:08:36,080 --> 00:08:36,280
heads,

246
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:36,460
heads,

247
00:08:36,460 --> 00:08:36,659
heads,

248
00:08:36,659 --> 00:08:37,179
or tails,

249
00:08:37,179 --> 00:08:37,500
tails,

250
00:08:37,500 --> 00:08:37,700
tails,

251
00:08:37,700 --> 00:08:38,000
tails,

252
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:38,200
tails.

253
00:08:39,600 --> 00:08:40,780
What about the other law?

254
00:08:41,039 --> 00:08:46,269
The one which says that the coin does

255
00:08:46,269 --> 00:08:51,500
flip between each successive flash of the stroboscope.

256
00:08:52,600 --> 00:08:53,360
That's easy.

257
00:08:53,580 --> 00:08:56,070
That just says sigma of t plus

258
00:08:56,070 --> 00:08:58,560
1 is equal to minus sigma of t.

259
00:08:59,300 --> 00:09:00,700
If it starts at 1,

260
00:09:00,700 --> 00:09:03,020
then at the next instant it's minus 1.

261
00:09:03,180 --> 00:09:04,100
If it starts at 1,

262
00:09:04,100 --> 00:09:07,420
then at the next instant it's the opposite.

263
00:09:07,900 --> 00:09:10,600
So there we've written down

264
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:13,300
equations of motion for a very,

265
00:09:13,300 --> 00:09:15,120
very simple system.

266
00:09:17,420 --> 00:09:20,480
Notice that it is completely predictive,

267
00:09:20,820 --> 00:09:21,680
completely deterministic.

268
00:09:23,700 --> 00:09:26,240
There's no ambiguity about what

269
00:09:26,240 --> 00:09:28,780
happens arbitrarily far down the future.

270
00:09:29,220 --> 00:09:29,660
Now,

271
00:09:29,660 --> 00:09:30,200
of course,

272
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:31,760
I could come in and grab the coin and

273
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:33,320
do something with it and do something else with it.

274
00:09:33,380 --> 00:09:34,260
That would disturb it.

275
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:36,920
In our language that we've set up now,

276
00:09:36,920 --> 00:09:39,780
that would be because the system was not closed.

277
00:09:41,079 --> 00:09:41,960
I intervened,

278
00:09:41,960 --> 00:09:43,400
and I was not part of the system.

279
00:09:43,840 --> 00:09:45,340
So for a closed system,

280
00:09:45,340 --> 00:09:47,220
laws of physics are

281
00:09:47,220 --> 00:09:49,100
completely deterministic in classical mechanics.

282
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:51,400
Okay.

283
00:09:51,480 --> 00:09:52,080
Now let's go.

284
00:09:52,500 --> 00:09:56,100
Let's think about a more complicated system.

285
00:09:59,660 --> 00:10:01,100
More complicated system,

286
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:02,560
not much more complicated.

287
00:10:03,140 --> 00:10:05,420
Instead of a coin,

288
00:10:05,420 --> 00:10:07,000
let's take,

289
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:07,960
what's the next case,

290
00:10:07,960 --> 00:10:08,280
friends?

291
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:10,340
