00:28:22,840 --> 00:28:24,140
Did you come from edges?

883
00:28:24,460 --> 00:28:24,720
Well,

884
00:28:24,720 --> 00:28:25,160
maybe.

885
00:28:27,460 --> 00:28:29,440
But you could have also come from heads.

886
00:28:30,720 --> 00:28:32,480
So while you can predict the future,

887
00:28:32,680 --> 00:28:33,920
you can't...

888
00:28:36,180 --> 00:28:36,640
redict?

889
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:37,800
What's the opposite of predict?

890
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:38,360
Retro-dict.

891
00:28:38,360 --> 00:28:38,680
Retro-dict.

892
00:28:38,760 --> 00:28:39,560
That's the word I'm looking for.

893
00:28:39,700 --> 00:28:43,540
You can't retro-dict the past from this law of motion.

894
00:28:47,040 --> 00:28:49,270
One configuration or several configurations

895
00:28:49,840 --> 00:28:52,840
run into the same configuration,

896
00:28:53,400 --> 00:28:55,660
and so you can't tell if you're over here

897
00:28:55,660 --> 00:28:57,100
whether you came from here or here.

898
00:28:57,900 --> 00:29:00,360
The word for this is that it's not reversible.

899
00:29:02,160 --> 00:29:03,600
Here's the way to think about it.

900
00:29:04,220 --> 00:29:05,680
Reverse every arrow.

901
00:29:13,100 --> 00:29:15,740
Now you have an un-predictive situation.

902
00:29:16,560 --> 00:29:17,680
If you're at tails,

903
00:29:17,840 --> 00:29:19,200
you don't know whether to go to heads

904
00:29:19,200 --> 00:29:20,620
or whether to go to edges.

905
00:29:21,939 --> 00:29:25,380
So it's a predictive situation one way,

906
00:29:25,440 --> 00:29:27,400
but not retro-dictive the other way.

907
00:29:27,480 --> 00:29:29,540
The word for this is not reversible.

908
00:29:29,880 --> 00:29:31,020
I won't call it irreversible.

909
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:32,220
That's a little too definite.

910
00:29:32,840 --> 00:29:34,160
It's not reversible.

911
00:29:36,280 --> 00:29:37,160
It can't...

912
00:29:37,160 --> 00:29:38,280
You can go one way,

913
00:29:38,280 --> 00:29:39,200
but not the other way.

914
00:29:40,140 --> 00:29:42,980
This is the kind of law that is not allowed

915
00:29:42,980 --> 00:29:44,180
in classical physics.

916
00:29:44,360 --> 00:29:44,460
Yes,

917
00:29:44,460 --> 00:29:44,580
sir?

918
00:29:44,760 --> 00:29:45,380
Ma'am,

919
00:29:45,380 --> 00:29:45,920
I can't see.

920
00:29:46,160 --> 00:29:47,640
Would a system like that be allowed

921
00:29:47,640 --> 00:29:49,180
in the probabilities of a particle?

922
00:29:49,200 --> 00:29:49,910
Would you be trying to

923
00:29:49,910 --> 00:29:50,620
get to the top of that?

924
00:29:50,760 --> 00:29:51,240
Well,

925
00:29:51,240 --> 00:29:52,300
um...

926
00:29:58,200 --> 00:29:58,680
Okay,

927
00:29:58,680 --> 00:29:59,880
that of course depends

928
00:29:59,880 --> 00:30:02,200
on what you're trying to represent.

929
00:30:06,220 --> 00:30:08,620
Classical physics doesn't allow probabilities,

930
00:30:08,700 --> 00:30:10,480
so I think I could escape from the question

931
00:30:10,480 --> 00:30:12,620
by just saying we don't do that in classical physics.

932
00:30:13,600 --> 00:30:15,320
But we could...

933
00:30:15,320 --> 00:30:16,820
We can imagine...

934
00:30:16,820 --> 00:30:17,060
Of course,

935
00:30:17,060 --> 00:30:18,500
we can imagine anything we want.

936
00:30:19,200 --> 00:30:19,200
In fact,

937
00:30:19,200 --> 00:30:20,700
we can imagine this.

938
00:30:22,040 --> 00:30:23,720
And we can study its properties.

939
00:30:26,420 --> 00:30:27,400
The point is,

940
00:30:27,400 --> 00:30:28,260
in one way or another,

941
00:30:28,520 --> 00:30:30,860
it conflicts with the rules of classical mechanics.

942
00:30:32,840 --> 00:30:33,360
Probability,

943
00:30:33,360 --> 00:30:36,000
or let's call it non-deterministic laws,

944
00:30:36,180 --> 00:30:40,000
also conflict with the rules of classical mechanics.

945
00:30:41,580 --> 00:30:43,460
So it's a very good question,

946
00:30:44,180 --> 00:30:46,660
and it's something we'll want to come back to,

947
00:30:46,660 --> 00:30:48,220
whether when...

948
00:30:48,220 --> 00:30:49,660
Quantum mechanics,

949
00:30:49,660 --> 00:30:50,320
for example,

950
00:30:50,320 --> 00:30:51,720
which is not deterministic,

951
00:30:51,880 --> 00:30:54,820
does quantum mechanics have an analog

952
00:30:54,820 --> 00:30:57,060
of this reversibility idea,

953
00:30:57,360 --> 00:30:59,860
even though it's not deterministic?

954
00:30:59,960 --> 00:31:00,560
And the answer is yes,

955
00:31:00,560 --> 00:31:01,960
but not tonight.

956
00:31:02,220 --> 00:31:04,160
Classical statistical mechanics...

957
00:31:04,160 --> 00:31:04,940
Well,

958
00:31:04,940 --> 00:31:08,220
classical statistical mechanics also has...

959
00:31:08,220 --> 00:31:11,320
Keep in mind that the rules

960
00:31:11,320 --> 00:31:13,300
of classical statistical mechanics

961
00:31:13,300 --> 00:31:16,300
begin with the laws of mechanics.

962
00:31:17,260 --> 00:31:17,860
Okay?

963
00:31:18,340 --> 00:31:20,460
We begin by assuming...

964
00:31:21,160 --> 00:31:21,460
All right,

965
00:31:21,460 --> 00:31:22,720
let's talk a little bit about

966
00:31:22,720 --> 00:31:26,080
the limits on predictability for a moment.

967
00:31:27,400 --> 00:31:31,760
If we have a perfectly predictive system of equations,

968
00:31:32,500 --> 00:31:35,600
it won't allow us to be completely predictive

969
00:31:35,600 --> 00:31:38,500
if we don't know the initial conditions exactly.

970
00:31:39,660 --> 00:31:40,940
So we need to know

971
00:31:40,940 --> 00:31:42,220
two things to predict the future.

972
00:31:42,220 --> 00:31:44,020
One is what the rules are,

973
00:31:44,140 --> 00:31:44,720
the laws,

974
00:31:44,920 --> 00:31:50,880
and one is what the initial conditions are.

975
00:31:51,520 --> 00:31:52,020
Now,

976
00:31:52,020 --> 00:31:53,180
in these very,

977
00:31:53,180 --> 00:31:54,500
very simple systems,

978
00:31:55,200 --> 00:31:58,300
it's easy to imagine that we could know exactly

979
00:31:58,300 --> 00:31:59,920
what the initial conditions are.

980
00:32:00,100 --> 00:32:00,440
Of course,

981
00:32:00,440 --> 00:32:00,920
we may not.

982
00:32:01,820 --> 00:32:04,060
We may know that we begin with either...

983
00:32:04,060 --> 00:32:04,540
Not this one,

984
00:32:04,540 --> 00:32:05,940
but this one.

985
00:32:06,040 --> 00:32:07,790
We may know that we

986
00:32:07,790 --> 00:32:09,540
begin either with edges or heads,

987
00:32:09,660 --> 00:32:10,300
we don't know which,

988
00:32:10,300 --> 00:32:13,680
and then there would be some ambiguity in what happens,

989
00:32:13,820 --> 00:32:17,020
not ambiguity because the equations have ambiguity in them,

990
00:32:17,160 --> 00:32:20,100
but because our knowledge of the initial state is imperfect.

991
00:32:20,580 --> 00:32:21,020
Okay?

992
00:32:21,120 --> 00:32:22,100
This is easy to understand.

993
00:32:22,520 --> 00:32:24,580
For these simple discrete systems,

994
00:32:24,700 --> 00:32:27,440
it's easy to imagine that we can do enough experiment

995
00:32:27,440 --> 00:32:31,060
and very quickly just look at a coin

996
00:32:31,060 --> 00:32:33,380
and know the initial condition perfectly.

997
00:32:34,460 --> 00:32:35,840
In the real world,

998
00:32:35,940 --> 00:32:39,720
where we're faced with degrees of freedom

999
00:32:39,720 --> 00:32:40,680
which are continuous,

1000
00:32:41,040 --> 00:32:43,210
meaning to say they can be

1001
00:32:43,210 --> 00:32:45,380
any number on the continuous real axis,

1002
00:32:45,640 --> 00:32:47,300
any number of numbers,

1003
00:32:47,600 --> 00:32:49,500
the positions and velocities of

1004
00:32:49,500 --> 00:32:51,400
all the particles in the world,

1005
00:32:52,100 --> 00:32:54,540
you can never know them perfectly.

1006
00:32:57,020 --> 00:32:59,980
No matter how many decimal points you may have

1007
00:33:00,720 --> 00:33:02,140
that you may have measured,

1008
00:33:03,200 --> 00:33:05,030
decimal places you may have measured

1009
00:33:05,030 --> 00:33:06,860
about the location of a particle,

1010
00:33:07,100 --> 00:33:08,960
you still don't know it exactly.

1011
00:33:10,060 --> 00:33:10,660
So,

1012
00:33:10,660 --> 00:33:13,900
there is always a degree of ambiguity

1013
00:33:13,900 --> 00:33:15,840
in your knowledge of the initial conditions.

1014
00:33:16,640 --> 00:33:20,360
That degree of ambiguity may or may not

1015
00:33:21,260 --> 00:33:23,180
sort of blow up in your face

1016
00:33:23,660 --> 00:33:27,440
that small changes in what the initial conditions are

1017
00:33:27,440 --> 00:33:29,910
may or may not give rise to

1018
00:33:29,910 --> 00:33:32,380
large changes in what happens in the future.

1019
00:33:34,040 --> 00:33:35,940
So the right way to say it is,

1020
00:33:36,080 --> 00:33:37,320
if you knew,

1021
00:33:37,560 --> 00:33:38,360
well,

1022
00:33:38,360 --> 00:33:39,520
we have to be quantitative,

1023
00:33:39,720 --> 00:33:42,240
but if you knew the initial conditions perfectly,

1024
00:33:42,620 --> 00:33:45,460
then you could predict the future forever and ever

1025
00:33:45,460 --> 00:33:47,160
in a true classical mechanical system,

1026
00:33:47,380 --> 00:33:50,020
and you could also predict the past perfectly.

1027
00:33:50,720 --> 00:33:54,260
If you have imperfect knowledge of the initial conditions,

1028
00:33:54,360 --> 00:33:56,400
you want to quantify that.

1029
00:33:56,520 --> 00:33:57,720
How imperfect is it?

1030
00:33:58,040 --> 00:33:59,900
And if you can quantify it,

1031
00:33:59,940 --> 00:34:01,860
it may allow you to answer the question,

1032
00:34:01,960 --> 00:34:04,920
how long into the future can you predict things?

1033
00:34:05,680 --> 00:34:06,240
So,

1034
00:34:06,240 --> 00:34:08,320
if you knew enough about

1035
00:34:08,320 --> 00:34:10,880
the initial conditions of the atmosphere,

1036
00:34:11,620 --> 00:34:13,020
you might be able to

1037
00:34:13,020 --> 00:34:14,420
predict the weather for three days.

1038
00:34:15,800 --> 00:34:16,320
But,

1039
00:34:16,320 --> 00:34:18,300
because your knowledge is limited,

1040
00:34:18,400 --> 00:34:20,840
and because the atmosphere is one of these systems

1041
00:34:20,840 --> 00:34:22,280
where little errors build up,

1042
00:34:22,360 --> 00:34:23,199
they're called chaotic,

1043
00:34:23,780 --> 00:34:25,480
because the atmosphere is chaotic,

1044
00:34:26,139 --> 00:34:29,179
no matter how well you know the initial conditions,

1045
00:34:29,540 --> 00:34:31,980
it is always true that if you wait long enough,

1046
00:34:32,820 --> 00:34:34,699
you won't be able to predict the future.

1047
00:34:34,860 --> 00:34:35,960
On the other hand,

1048
00:34:35,960 --> 00:34:36,659
if you say,

1049
00:34:36,659 --> 00:34:38,139
I want to be able to predict

1050
00:34:38,139 --> 00:34:39,620
the future for X number of years,

1051
00:34:40,020 --> 00:34:42,780
it should be possible to say how precisely

1052
00:34:42,780 --> 00:34:44,520
you have to know the initial conditions.

1053
00:34:45,620 --> 00:34:46,139
Okay,

1054
00:34:46,139 --> 00:34:46,659
so,

1055
00:34:46,659 --> 00:34:49,540
when we come to the real world,

1056
00:34:49,760 --> 00:34:51,370
this idea of predictability

1057
00:34:51,370 --> 00:34:52,980
becomes a little more complicated.

1058
00:34:53,400 --> 00:34:56,900
But I started on purpose with very simple discrete systems.

1059
00:34:58,380 --> 00:34:58,900
Okay,

1060
00:34:58,900 --> 00:34:59,340
so,

1061
00:34:59,340 --> 00:35:00,740
laws that are allowed,

1062
00:35:00,940 --> 00:35:02,060
laws that are not allowed,

1063
00:35:02,180 --> 00:35:06,500
laws of classical mechanics,

1064
00:35:06,660 --> 00:35:09,320
are not only deterministic into the future,

1065
00:35:09,480 --> 00:35:11,860
but they're deterministic into the past,

1066
00:35:12,060 --> 00:35:13,180
which makes them reversible.

1067
00:35:13,760 --> 00:35:14,280
Now,

1068
00:35:14,280 --> 00:35:15,600
how do you look at one of these pictures

1069
00:35:15,600 --> 00:35:18,660
and decide whether it's a legal law or not?

1070
00:35:19,040 --> 00:35:19,420
Well,

1071
00:35:19,420 --> 00:35:20,180
it's very simple.

1072
00:35:20,500 --> 00:35:24,940
If every state has one outgoing and one incoming arrow,

1073
00:35:26,400 --> 00:35:29,700
that means that you know where it came from

1074
00:35:29,700 --> 00:35:30,860
and where it's going.

1075
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:32,520
So,

1076
00:35:32,520 --> 00:35:34,160
when you draw one of these pictures,

1077
00:35:34,240 --> 00:35:36,540
if you want to know whether it is,

1078
00:35:36,660 --> 00:35:38,360
is an allowable legal law,

1079
00:35:38,460 --> 00:35:39,540
in the sense that I've defined,

1080
00:35:40,260 --> 00:35:43,440
I'm using legal now just

1081
00:35:43,440 --> 00:35:46,620
as a term for reversible systems.

1082
00:35:46,940 --> 00:35:48,680
If you want to know whether it's reversible,

1083
00:35:48,880 --> 00:35:49,540
look at the arrows,

1084
00:35:49,820 --> 00:35:53,280
and if each state has one incoming

1085
00:35:53,280 --> 00:35:54,560
and only one incoming,

1086
00:35:54,860 --> 00:35:56,080
and one outgoing,

1087
00:35:56,080 --> 00:35:57,240
only one outgoing,

1088
00:35:58,180 --> 00:36:01,800
then it is both deterministic and reversible.

1089
00:36:03,660 --> 00:36:05,080
There are analogs of all

1090
00:36:05,080 --> 00:36:06,500
the things I'm telling you now,

1091
00:36:06,660 --> 00:36:09,960
about more complex systems and more interesting systems,

1092
00:36:10,160 --> 00:36:12,180
such as particles moving around.

1093
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:15,620
Okay,

1094
00:36:15,620 --> 00:36:18,700
so that's sort of warm-up preliminary

1095
00:36:18,700 --> 00:36:20,900
about what classical mechanics is about.

1096
00:36:21,430 --> 00:36:22,800
It's about predicting the future,

1097
00:36:24,020 --> 00:36:25,810
or using the predictability,

1098
00:36:26,360 --> 00:36:28,480
the fact that in principle you could predict the future,

1099
00:36:28,660 --> 00:36:29,900
in other ways,

1100
00:36:29,900 --> 00:36:31,240
such as statistical ways,

1101
00:36:31,380 --> 00:36:34,880
to limit

1102
00:36:35,820 --> 00:36:37,220
what will happen.

1103
00:36:40,320 --> 00:36:41,000
All right,

1104
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:42,280
now we want to move on

1105
00:36:43,020 --> 00:36:45,080
to a more realistic world,

1106
00:36:45,160 --> 00:36:46,760
and in fact the world of particles.

1107
00:36:46,960 --> 00:36:48,320
We're going to be interested

1108
00:36:48,320 --> 00:36:49,680
in the world of particles moving,

1109
00:36:49,800 --> 00:36:51,370
and a particle for our purposes can

1110
00:36:51,370 --> 00:36:52,940
be thought of as a point particle.

1111
00:36:53,440 --> 00:36:55,980
If we want to make a more complicated system,

1112
00:36:56,120 --> 00:36:57,780
we'll make systems of particles,

1113
00:36:57,780 --> 00:36:58,440
points particles,

1114
00:36:59,560 --> 00:37:04,200
but we'll consider point particles moving around in space.

1115
00:37:05,600 --> 00:37:06,040
So,

1116
00:37:11,420 --> 00:37:12,680
what do we have to know?

1117
00:37:12,760 --> 00:37:16,400
What are the configurations of a point particle?

1118
00:37:16,720 --> 00:37:17,580
What do we need to know?

1119
00:37:20,200 --> 00:37:20,640
Well,

1120
00:37:20,640 --> 00:37:21,040
okay,

1121
00:37:21,040 --> 00:37:21,960
before we do so,

1122
00:37:22,400 --> 00:37:24,840
I think we should do

1123
00:37:24,840 --> 00:37:27,280
a little bit of mathematical preliminary.

1124
00:37:30,100 --> 00:37:31,460
I want to remind you,

1125
00:37:31,460 --> 00:37:32,540
for those who don't know,

1126
00:37:32,620 --> 00:37:33,760
or who know,

1127
00:37:33,760 --> 00:37:34,200
knew,

1128
00:37:34,200 --> 00:37:34,860
but don't know,

1129
00:37:34,880 --> 00:37:35,160
remember,

1130
00:37:35,740 --> 00:37:36,340
or remember,

1131
00:37:36,340 --> 00:37:37,340
but just barely,

1132
00:37:37,460 --> 00:37:41,180
what vectors are and what coordinate frames are.

1133
00:37:41,820 --> 00:37:44,050
A coordinate system is just

1134
00:37:44,050 --> 00:37:46,280
a way of describing space quantitatively.

1135
00:37:53,760 --> 00:37:54,780
And incidentally,

1136
00:37:54,780 --> 00:37:56,140
for our purposes today,

1137
00:37:56,300 --> 00:37:58,540
and largely in general,

1138
00:37:59,560 --> 00:38:00,320
we will,

1139
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:00,660
of course,

1140
00:38:00,660 --> 00:38:02,560
assume that space is three-dimensional.

1141
00:38:03,240 --> 00:38:04,040
And so,

1142
00:38:04,040 --> 00:38:04,740
a point of space

1143
00:38:04,880 --> 00:38:06,640
will be labeled by three coordinates.

1144
00:38:06,960 --> 00:38:10,860
But we're perfectly free to think about systems

1145
00:38:10,860 --> 00:38:13,440
which are higher dimensional or lower dimensional,

1146
00:38:13,720 --> 00:38:15,520
and we will do so.

1147
00:38:15,640 --> 00:38:18,620
Since we're interested in formulating the basic principles,

1148
00:38:18,940 --> 00:38:21,620
we don't have to restrict ourselves to very,

1149
00:38:21,620 --> 00:38:22,940
very specific examples.

1150
00:38:23,440 --> 00:38:26,160
A particle could move in one direction,

1151
00:38:26,160 --> 00:38:26,940
one dimension.

1152
00:38:27,120 --> 00:38:28,320
It can move in five dimensions,

1153
00:38:28,540 --> 00:38:31,840
and we will be interested in all the possibilities.

1154
00:38:32,600 --> 00:38:33,840
But for the moment,

1155
00:38:33,840 --> 00:38:35,320
let's just think of particles as

1156
00:38:35,320 --> 00:38:36,800
things which move in three dimensions.

1157
00:38:37,960 --> 00:38:39,950
So in order to be

1158
00:38:39,950 --> 00:38:41,940
quantitative about the location of particles,

1159
00:38:42,060 --> 00:38:43,780
we introduce a coordinate system.

1160
00:38:44,200 --> 00:38:45,100
Coordinate system,

1161
00:38:45,100 --> 00:38:46,340
Cartesian coordinates,

1162
00:38:46,460 --> 00:38:48,060
will be the usual things we'll introduce.

1163
00:38:49,280 --> 00:38:50,300
Later on,

1164
00:38:50,300 --> 00:38:52,150
we'll introduce other ways

1165
00:38:52,150 --> 00:38:54,000
of describing locations of particles.

1166
00:38:54,600 --> 00:38:55,540
But for the moment,

1167
00:38:57,260 --> 00:38:58,500
we take space,

1168
00:38:58,640 --> 00:39:00,620
we identify an origin.

1169
00:39:01,160 --> 00:39:04,150
The origin is up to us

1170
00:39:04,150 --> 00:39:07,140
where we want to put it.

1171
00:39:07,180 --> 00:39:07,940
I can put it over here,

1172
00:39:07,940 --> 00:39:08,840
I can put it over here.

1173
00:39:09,640 --> 00:39:11,620
It should be that the

1174
00:39:11,620 --> 00:39:13,600
important questions that we're interested in

1175
00:39:13,600 --> 00:39:15,780
should not depend on the convention

1176
00:39:15,780 --> 00:39:17,960
of where we put the origin,

1177
00:39:18,220 --> 00:39:20,840
but it's useful to fix it once and for all

1178
00:39:20,840 --> 00:39:24,060
and say the origin of

1179
00:39:24,060 --> 00:39:27,280
coordinates is located in Palo Alto,

1180
00:39:27,440 --> 00:39:29,140
wherever we want to put it.

1181
00:39:30,020 --> 00:39:30,940
Here it is.

1182
00:39:32,140 --> 00:39:33,600
Then introduce axes.

1183
00:39:33,960 --> 00:39:36,380
The axes are taken to be mutually perpendicular.

1184
00:39:36,700 --> 00:39:38,600
You can check that they're perpendicular by,

1185
00:39:39,400 --> 00:39:41,560
with a T square or whatever it

1186
00:39:41,560 --> 00:39:43,720
is that you use to align axes.

1187
00:39:44,220 --> 00:39:45,400
And you label them.

1188
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:46,760
You can label them X,

1189
00:39:46,760 --> 00:39:47,040
Y,

1190
00:39:47,040 --> 00:39:47,420
and Z.

1191
00:39:50,800 --> 00:39:51,840
Or X1,

1192
00:39:51,840 --> 00:39:52,400
X2,

1193
00:39:52,400 --> 00:39:53,060
and X3.

1194
00:39:53,200 --> 00:39:54,820
We'll use both kinds of notations.

1195
00:39:55,620 --> 00:39:59,080
But there's also an ambiguity about the orientation.

1196
00:39:59,080 --> 00:39:59,980
The orientation of the axes,

1197
00:39:59,980 --> 00:40:01,740
given that they're mutually perpendicular,

1198
00:40:02,380 --> 00:40:03,980
we still have to decide,

1199
00:40:04,260 --> 00:40:04,640
you know,

1200
00:40:04,640 --> 00:40:05,860
I don't know how to draw this,

1201
00:40:05,960 --> 00:40:07,040
I think you know what I mean,

1202
00:40:07,160 --> 00:40:09,500
which directions they go in.

1203
00:40:09,920 --> 00:40:13,900
And so that's like fixing the origin of coordinates.

1204
00:40:13,980 --> 00:40:16,320
We also have to fix an

1205
00:40:16,320 --> 00:40:18,660
orientation for the X and Y axis.

1206
00:40:18,820 --> 00:40:20,120
Once we fix the orientation

1207
00:40:20,120 --> 00:40:21,420
for the X and Y axis,

1208
00:40:21,680 --> 00:40:23,140
the third one is fixed.

1209
00:40:23,180 --> 00:40:24,360
It's perpendicular to it.

1210
00:40:24,880 --> 00:40:25,360
Incidentally,

1211
00:40:25,360 --> 00:40:26,060
there's a convention,

1212
00:40:26,660 --> 00:40:28,540
and the convention is called

1213
00:40:29,080 --> 00:40:30,340
the right-handed coordinate system.

1214
00:40:30,640 --> 00:40:33,240
The convention is when you've picked X and Y,

1215
00:40:33,780 --> 00:40:38,100
you still need to know one discrete piece of information.

1216
00:40:38,500 --> 00:40:40,620
Is Z pointing out of the blackboard,

1217
00:40:40,680 --> 00:40:42,280
or is it pointing into the blackboard?

1218
00:40:42,780 --> 00:40:45,580
And we settle on that by a rule.

1219
00:40:45,800 --> 00:40:46,520
It's a convention.

1220
00:40:46,740 --> 00:40:47,320
It's arbitrary.

1221
00:40:47,720 --> 00:40:48,680
The right-hand rule.

1222
00:40:49,060 --> 00:40:52,120
If we take our thumb and our index finger,

1223
00:40:52,280 --> 00:40:53,740
thumb along X,

1224
00:40:53,740 --> 00:40:55,180
index finger along Y,

1225
00:40:55,360 --> 00:40:57,080
then Z is the middle finger,

1226
00:40:57,200 --> 00:40:58,860
the direction of the middle finger.

1227
00:40:59,080 --> 00:40:59,620
Right.

1228
00:40:59,820 --> 00:41:01,800
So that's the right-hand rule,

1229
00:41:02,040 --> 00:41:05,740
and it selects out this coordinate system

1230
00:41:05,740 --> 00:41:07,290
from the other one where

1231
00:41:07,290 --> 00:41:08,840
Z goes in the other direction.

1232
00:41:09,260 --> 00:41:09,900
Okay.

1233
00:41:09,980 --> 00:41:13,400
So that's the idea of a right-handed coordinate system.

1234
00:41:13,740 --> 00:41:17,440
We also have to mark off distances along here.

1235
00:41:17,760 --> 00:41:22,760
So distances are marked off equal distances

1236
00:41:23,520 --> 00:41:24,620
with a ruler.

1237
00:41:27,860 --> 00:41:29,020
And of course,

1238
00:41:29,020 --> 00:41:30,900
in saying that we mark off distances,

1239
00:41:31,380 --> 00:41:35,360
we're also assuming a set of units.

1240
00:41:36,240 --> 00:41:38,060
The units could be meters,

1241
00:41:38,060 --> 00:41:39,240
it could be inches,

1242
00:41:39,440 --> 00:41:40,360
it could be feet,

1243
00:41:40,360 --> 00:41:41,280
it could be light years.

1244
00:41:41,840 --> 00:41:43,580
So again,

1245
00:41:43,580 --> 00:41:44,680
another,

1246
00:41:44,680 --> 00:41:45,940
not ambiguity,

1247
00:41:46,060 --> 00:41:49,300
but another convention is to choose our units.

1248
00:41:49,520 --> 00:41:51,680
But once we've chosen our units,

1249
00:41:51,960 --> 00:41:53,900
we can lay off distances along here.

1250
00:41:54,620 --> 00:41:56,180
And then every point in space

1251
00:41:58,400 --> 00:42:01,220
can be labeled by the value of X,

1252
00:42:01,220 --> 00:42:01,640
Y,

1253
00:42:01,640 --> 00:42:02,160
and Z.

1254
00:42:03,880 --> 00:42:04,360
Let's see,

1255
00:42:04,360 --> 00:42:05,080
how do we draw this?

1256
00:42:06,480 --> 00:42:06,840
Um...

1257
00:42:15,959 --> 00:42:17,020
It has a height,

1258
00:42:17,020 --> 00:42:17,380
Y.

1259
00:42:19,240 --> 00:42:20,140
It has an X,

1260
00:42:20,140 --> 00:42:20,520
X,

1261
00:42:20,520 --> 00:42:21,680
and it has a Z,

1262
00:42:21,680 --> 00:42:22,000
Z.

1263
00:42:22,420 --> 00:42:23,060
If you like,

1264
00:42:23,060 --> 00:42:23,920
you can think about,

1265
00:42:23,920 --> 00:42:25,940
how do you get to this point from the origin?

1266
00:42:26,280 --> 00:42:28,860
You go a certain number of steps along X,

1267
00:42:29,020 --> 00:42:30,720
you go a certain number of steps along Y,

1268
00:42:30,880 --> 00:42:32,080
and then you go a

1269
00:42:32,080 --> 00:42:33,280
certain number of steps along Z.

1270
00:42:33,720 --> 00:42:35,520
And those quantities,

1271
00:42:35,520 --> 00:42:35,920
X,

1272
00:42:35,920 --> 00:42:36,240
Y,

1273
00:42:36,240 --> 00:42:36,700
and Z,

1274
00:42:36,840 --> 00:42:38,860
are the coordinates of the point.

1275
00:42:39,320 --> 00:42:42,420
So a point is labeled by a set X,

1276
00:42:42,420 --> 00:42:42,900
Y,

1277
00:42:42,900 --> 00:42:43,240
and Z.

1278
00:42:43,340 --> 00:42:43,440
Now,

1279
00:42:43,440 --> 00:42:44,360
I know you all know this,

1280
00:42:44,980 --> 00:42:46,420
but let's spell it out anyway.

1281
00:42:48,920 --> 00:42:49,320
Okay,

1282
00:42:49,320 --> 00:42:51,200
so that's the way we describe a point.

1283
00:42:51,260 --> 00:42:52,520
That's the way we describe a particle.

1284
00:42:54,100 --> 00:42:55,080
And of course,

1285
00:42:55,080 --> 00:42:56,480
if we have a system of particles,

1286
00:42:56,640 --> 00:42:57,400
many particles,

1287
00:42:57,400 --> 00:42:58,840
then of course,

1288
00:42:58,840 --> 00:43:00,840
we just have to put in

1289
00:43:00,840 --> 00:43:02,840
one such point for each particle.

1290
00:43:05,660 --> 00:43:06,260
Okay,

1291
00:43:06,260 --> 00:43:06,860
vectors.

1292
00:43:07,020 --> 00:43:08,120
What is a vector?

1293
00:43:08,440 --> 00:43:12,250
A vector is an object

1294
00:43:12,250 --> 00:43:16,060
which has both length and direction.

1295
00:43:16,640 --> 00:43:17,600
For example,

1296
00:43:17,600 --> 00:43:19,280
a very simple vector

1297
00:43:20,840 --> 00:43:22,980
is the position of this point

1298
00:43:22,980 --> 00:43:24,680
relative to the origin.

1299
00:43:24,960 --> 00:43:25,880
Here's the origin,

1300
00:43:26,600 --> 00:43:29,740
and the position of this point relative to the origin

1301
00:43:29,740 --> 00:43:30,740
has a magnitude,

1302
00:43:30,740 --> 00:43:32,540
which is the distance from the origin,

1303
00:43:32,800 --> 00:43:34,620
and it has a direction,

1304
00:43:34,760 --> 00:43:37,030
namely just the direction of the

1305
00:43:37,030 --> 00:43:39,300
arrow connecting the point with here.

1306
00:43:41,720 --> 00:43:42,960
Think of that vector

1307
00:43:43,820 --> 00:43:48,680
as an object which has a length and a direction,

1308
00:43:48,960 --> 00:43:51,700
but don't think of it as being located anywhere.

1309
00:43:51,700 --> 00:43:55,460
Think of it as being the same

1310
00:43:55,460 --> 00:43:59,220
no matter where I draw it in space.

1311
00:43:59,520 --> 00:44:00,000
In fact,

1312
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:00,990
I don't even have to

1313
00:44:00,990 --> 00:44:01,980
think about drawing it in space.

1314
00:44:02,360 --> 00:44:03,560
It is what it is.

1315
00:44:03,720 --> 00:44:06,460
It's a magnitude and a direction in space.

1316
00:44:06,760 --> 00:44:07,680
That's called a vector.

1317
00:44:08,440 --> 00:44:09,680
And from now on,

1318
00:44:09,680 --> 00:44:11,200
we will label vectors

1319
00:44:15,380 --> 00:44:18,000
by putting a little bar on top of them.

1320
00:44:18,360 --> 00:44:20,080
If I'm really conscientious,

1321
00:44:20,140 --> 00:44:21,680
I'll put a little arrow on top of them.

1322
00:44:21,680 --> 00:44:24,040
If I forget the top of the arrow,

1323
00:44:24,120 --> 00:44:25,500
or I get bored writing arrows,

1324
00:44:25,620 --> 00:44:27,220
I'll just put a little bar on top.

1325
00:44:27,820 --> 00:44:29,160
And here and there,

1326
00:44:29,240 --> 00:44:31,360
I may even forget to put anything on top,

1327
00:44:31,520 --> 00:44:32,860
but you'll remind me.

1328
00:44:33,360 --> 00:44:33,920
Okay,

1329
00:44:33,920 --> 00:44:36,040
so a vector has a magnitude.

1330
00:44:36,420 --> 00:44:38,220
The magnitude is its length.

1331
00:44:38,500 --> 00:44:41,200
It does not have to necessarily be

1332
00:44:42,140 --> 00:44:43,660
a relative position.

1333
00:44:44,200 --> 00:44:45,500
It could be a velocity,

1334
00:44:45,700 --> 00:44:46,560
it could be an acceleration,

1335
00:44:47,020 --> 00:44:49,120
something that...or other things.

1336
00:44:49,460 --> 00:44:51,660
It could be an electric current,

1337
00:44:51,680 --> 00:44:52,060
electric field,

1338
00:44:52,260 --> 00:44:53,700
it could be all sorts of things.

1339
00:44:53,840 --> 00:44:55,480
The criteria for it to be a vector

1340
00:44:55,480 --> 00:44:57,960
is that it has a length and a direction.

1341
00:44:58,980 --> 00:44:59,420
Okay,

1342
00:44:59,420 --> 00:45:01,120
so that's the notion of a vector.

1343
00:45:01,280 --> 00:45:04,060
Every vector can be described

1344
00:45:05,759 --> 00:45:08,240
or has associated with it a length.

1345
00:45:08,380 --> 00:45:10,000
Let's call the length of it...

1346
00:45:10,920 --> 00:45:11,700
In fact,

1347
00:45:11,700 --> 00:45:12,520
for the length of it,

1348
00:45:12,560 --> 00:45:13,680
I don't have to put a vector sign.

1349
00:45:14,600 --> 00:45:16,720
Two bars on either side of it,

1350
00:45:16,780 --> 00:45:18,420
the absolute value of it,

1351
00:45:18,980 --> 00:45:20,340
are called its length.

1352
00:45:20,340 --> 00:45:22,100
So this is a way of writing its length.

1353
00:45:23,060 --> 00:45:24,540
So that's the length of the vector.

1354
00:45:25,020 --> 00:45:25,840
And the vector,

1355
00:45:25,840 --> 00:45:26,700
it's always positive,

1356
00:45:27,240 --> 00:45:27,680
or zero,

1357
00:45:27,680 --> 00:45:28,520
it could be zero.

1358
00:45:28,620 --> 00:45:30,200
If the vector has no length at all,

1359
00:45:30,440 --> 00:45:31,180
in other words,

1360
00:45:31,180 --> 00:45:32,580
if this point were right at the origin,

1361
00:45:32,700 --> 00:45:33,660
it would have no length at all,

1362
00:45:34,140 --> 00:45:36,360
it's always either positive or zero.

1363
00:45:36,580 --> 00:45:38,300
So every vector has a length,

1364
00:45:38,900 --> 00:45:40,100
and it has a direction,

1365
00:45:40,200 --> 00:45:41,700
which is not so easy to write down.

1366
00:45:43,500 --> 00:45:45,880
It can also be described by components.

1367
00:45:46,600 --> 00:45:48,860
The components of the vector

1368
00:45:48,860 --> 00:45:50,280
are exactly what I said before,

1369
00:45:50,280 --> 00:45:53,300
if you wanted to go from the origin

1370
00:45:53,300 --> 00:45:55,160
to this point over here,

1371
00:45:55,260 --> 00:45:57,100
you would go a certain number of units of x,

1372
00:45:57,220 --> 00:45:58,360
a certain number of units of y,

1373
00:45:58,440 --> 00:45:59,720
and a certain number of units of z.

1374
00:46:00,400 --> 00:46:01,960
The other way to define it

1375
00:46:01,960 --> 00:46:03,920
is to drop a perpendicular

1376
00:46:05,259 --> 00:46:08,160
from the point to each one of the axes.

1377
00:46:09,259 --> 00:46:11,120
I don't draw this very well.

1378
00:46:11,960 --> 00:46:12,640
Let's see,

1379
00:46:12,640 --> 00:46:13,200
I think...

1380
00:46:13,200 --> 00:46:14,260
How are we going to do this?

1381
00:46:14,820 --> 00:46:16,260
I want to get this vector

1382
00:46:16,260 --> 00:46:17,700
to be out of the blackboard.

1383
00:46:17,920 --> 00:46:18,840
How can I get it

1384
00:46:18,840 --> 00:46:19,760
to be out of the blackboard,

1385
00:46:19,760 --> 00:46:21,020
but draw it on the blackboard?

1386
00:46:21,120 --> 00:46:22,320
Any time I draw it on the blackboard,

1387
00:46:22,360 --> 00:46:23,660
it always looks like it's on the blackboard.

1388
00:46:24,360 --> 00:46:24,840
Okay.

1389
00:46:32,380 --> 00:46:33,960
From here to here.

1390
00:46:35,560 --> 00:46:36,040
Okay.

1391
00:46:36,580 --> 00:46:38,000
We drop a perpendicular

1392
00:46:38,700 --> 00:46:40,140
from the tip of the arrow

1393
00:46:40,140 --> 00:46:41,640
to each one of the axes,

1394
00:46:42,980 --> 00:46:44,840
and that lays off for us

1395
00:46:44,840 --> 00:46:46,740
a distance along those axes,

1396
00:46:46,900 --> 00:46:49,380
which are the three components of the vector.

1397
00:46:50,080 --> 00:46:52,420
We'll call them vx,

1398
00:46:52,420 --> 00:46:53,980
vy,

1399
00:46:53,980 --> 00:46:56,100
and vz.

1400
00:46:57,360 --> 00:46:58,800
When I'm writing the components,

1401
00:46:58,920 --> 00:47:00,050
I have no need to put

1402
00:47:00,050 --> 00:47:01,180
the arrow on top of them.

1403
00:47:01,280 --> 00:47:03,120
The components themselves are numbers.

1404
00:47:03,920 --> 00:47:04,400
Okay.

1405
00:47:06,120 --> 00:47:07,800
What is the length of this vector

1406
00:47:07,800 --> 00:47:09,500
whose components are vx,

1407
00:47:09,500 --> 00:47:09,780
vy,

1408
00:47:09,780 --> 00:47:10,460
and vz?

1409
00:47:11,340 --> 00:47:14,140
The squares of vx squared plus vy squared.

1410
00:47:14,140 --> 00:47:14,540
Yeah,

1411
00:47:14,540 --> 00:47:16,020
the square of the length

1412
00:47:16,020 --> 00:47:18,540
is vx squared plus vy squared plus vc squared.

1413
00:47:18,540 --> 00:47:19,540
Pythagoras'

1414
00:47:19,720 --> 00:47:20,040
theorem,

1415
00:47:20,220 --> 00:47:21,320
except in three dimensions.

1416
00:47:21,680 --> 00:47:22,700
I'll assume it.

1417
00:47:22,760 --> 00:47:23,520
We won't prove it.

1418
00:47:24,100 --> 00:47:25,700
That the length of v,

1419
00:47:26,439 --> 00:47:27,720
the magnitude of v,

1420
00:47:28,260 --> 00:47:29,560
is the square root

1421
00:47:31,620 --> 00:47:33,680
of the sums of the components.

1422
00:47:42,520 --> 00:47:44,580
That's the notion of the magnitude of a vector.

1423
00:47:45,200 --> 00:47:48,380
And the direction of the vector

1424
00:47:48,540 --> 00:47:51,720
is encoded in the ratios

1425
00:47:51,720 --> 00:47:53,000
of the different components.

1426
00:47:53,480 --> 00:47:54,420
For example,

1427
00:47:54,420 --> 00:47:55,320
if the x component

1428
00:47:55,320 --> 00:47:57,240
is much bigger than the y component,

1429
00:47:57,420 --> 00:47:59,100
then the vector is pointed more or less

1430
00:47:59,100 --> 00:48:00,720
along the x axis and so forth.

1431
00:48:01,760 --> 00:48:03,920
The components can be positive or negative.

1432
00:48:04,160 --> 00:48:04,920
If they're negative,

1433
00:48:05,120 --> 00:48:07,480
they're pointing along the negative axis and so forth.

1434
00:48:08,340 --> 00:48:09,000
All right,

1435
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:11,200
but as I want to emphasize now,

1436
00:48:11,860 --> 00:48:12,380
again,

1437
00:48:12,620 --> 00:48:14,680
that the notion of a vector

1438
00:48:14,680 --> 00:48:17,540
is not necessarily tied

1439
00:48:17,540 --> 00:48:21,480
to the location of anything in space.

1440
00:48:22,380 --> 00:48:23,960
It is what it is.

1441
00:48:24,360 --> 00:48:27,660
It's a length or a magnitude and a direction.

1442
00:48:27,920 --> 00:48:29,240
And if you move it around,

1443
00:48:29,520 --> 00:48:31,780
it doesn't change the vector.

1444
00:48:32,920 --> 00:48:34,640
That's just a mathematical definition

1445
00:48:34,640 --> 00:48:35,980
of the way you think about vectors.

1446
00:48:36,300 --> 00:48:38,040
You don't think of them as being tied

1447
00:48:38,040 --> 00:48:39,140
to a point in space.

1448
00:48:39,760 --> 00:48:40,440
You can.

1449
00:48:40,700 --> 00:48:40,840
I mean,

1450
00:48:40,840 --> 00:48:41,440
there are circumstances

1451
00:48:41,440 --> 00:48:42,860
when you may want to tie

1452
00:48:42,860 --> 00:48:44,900
a vector to a point in space.

1453
00:48:45,100 --> 00:48:45,440
For example,

1454
00:48:45,540 --> 00:48:46,820
you might want to ask,

1455
00:48:46,860 --> 00:48:47,520
what is the alignment

1456
00:48:47,520 --> 00:48:48,180
of an electric field

1457
00:48:48,180 --> 00:48:50,060
at a particular point of space?

1458
00:48:50,660 --> 00:48:52,140
Then that vector is tied

1459
00:48:52,140 --> 00:48:53,680
to that particular point in space.

1460
00:48:54,260 --> 00:48:57,080
But the notion of a vector transcends that.

1461
00:48:57,200 --> 00:48:58,280
It doesn't matter where you put it.

1462
00:48:59,100 --> 00:48:59,660
All right,

1463
00:48:59,660 --> 00:49:00,740
now we have to talk about

1464
00:49:00,740 --> 00:49:02,320
the algebra of vectors.

1465
00:49:06,840 --> 00:49:08,260
I really feel sorry

1466
00:49:08,260 --> 00:49:09,320
for all of you people

1467
00:49:09,320 --> 00:49:10,480
who've sat through this

1468
00:49:10,480 --> 00:49:12,060
endless number of times before,

1469
00:49:12,280 --> 00:49:12,720
but...

1470
00:49:22,240 --> 00:49:22,880
At this point...

1471
00:49:24,919 --> 00:49:25,240
Let's...

1472
00:49:29,500 --> 00:49:30,080
That's funny.

1473
00:49:30,180 --> 00:49:30,960
There are some things,

1474
00:49:32,740 --> 00:49:33,580
like a book,

1475
00:49:34,899 --> 00:49:35,220
which,

1476
00:49:35,220 --> 00:49:36,640
no matter how good the book is,

1477
00:49:36,700 --> 00:49:37,360
pretty much,

1478
00:49:37,460 --> 00:49:38,100
except for some

1479
00:49:38,100 --> 00:49:39,580
extremely special cases,

1480
00:49:39,820 --> 00:49:41,200
you really only want to read it once.

1481
00:49:41,900 --> 00:49:42,280
You know,

1482
00:49:42,340 --> 00:49:43,720
you may say you want to read that book

1483
00:49:43,720 --> 00:49:44,860
because you love that book so much

1484
00:49:44,860 --> 00:49:45,660
you could read it endlessly.

1485
00:49:45,880 --> 00:49:46,660
But it's not really true.

1486
00:49:46,760 --> 00:49:47,220
You read it...

1487
00:49:47,520 --> 00:49:47,820
once.

1488
00:49:47,820 --> 00:49:50,220
There are other things like a good

1489
00:49:50,220 --> 00:49:52,620
piece of music which you want to hear

1490
00:49:52,620 --> 00:49:54,750
over and over and it doesn't

1491
00:49:54,750 --> 00:49:56,880
matter how many times you've heard it,

1492
00:49:56,880 --> 00:49:58,240
it just is

1493
00:49:58,240 --> 00:49:59,360
always good to hear.

1494
00:49:59,360 --> 00:50:01,400
I assume my lectures are like that.

1495
00:50:11,240 --> 00:50:14,340
Alright so let's talk about the algebra of vectors.

1496
00:50:14,340 --> 00:50:15,960
The algebra of vectors,

1497
00:50:15,960 --> 00:50:16,220
first

1498
00:50:16,220 --> 00:50:17,200
of all you can add them,

1499
00:50:17,200 --> 00:50:19,040
you can subtract them,

1500
00:50:19,040 --> 00:50:20,660
your can multiply them by numbers,

1501
00:50:21,160 --> 00:50:22,960
so let's talk about that a little bit.

1502
00:50:23,960 --> 00:50:24,940
Given a vector,

1503
00:50:24,940 --> 00:50:26,540
let's call the vector A,

1504
00:50:26,540 --> 00:50:31,020
again it's a length and it's a direction

1505
00:50:31,020 --> 00:50:33,440
you can multiply it by a number,

1506
00:50:33,440 --> 00:50:36,720
an ordinary number but a real

1507
00:50:36,720 --> 00:50:37,040
number.

1508
00:50:37,480 --> 00:50:39,420
Let's multiply it by the number C,

1509
00:50:41,280 --> 00:50:42,620
what's the definition of that?

1510
00:50:42,620 --> 00:50:44,600
It depends on where the C is positive or negative.

1511
00:50:44,900 --> 00:50:46,200
If C is positive

1512
00:50:46,940 --> 00:50:49,920
it's a vector along the same direction

1513
00:50:49,920 --> 00:50:52,900
except its length is multiplied by C.

1514
00:50:54,020 --> 00:50:56,370
So twice a vector means a vector of

1515
00:50:56,370 --> 00:50:58,720
exactly the same direction but twice as long,

1516
00:50:58,880 --> 00:51:00,080
and so forth and so on.

1517
00:51:00,840 --> 00:51:04,920
We can also define the negative of a vector.

1518
00:51:05,880 --> 00:51:06,800
In other words,

1519
00:51:06,800 --> 00:51:08,440
we could let C be minus 1.

1520
00:51:09,280 --> 00:51:10,970
I can either put here minus

1521
00:51:10,970 --> 00:51:12,660
1 or just minus the vector.

1522
00:51:13,540 --> 00:51:14,700
And of course,

1523
00:51:14,700 --> 00:51:16,780
the negative of a vector is exactly

1524
00:51:16,780 --> 00:51:18,860
the same vector except with a direction

1525
00:51:18,860 --> 00:51:20,820
in the opposite direction.

1526
00:51:22,620 --> 00:51:26,640
That's the definition of multiplying a vector by a number,

1527
00:51:26,640 --> 00:51:27,600
by an ordinary number.

1528
00:51:28,620 --> 00:51:30,460
Now you can also add vectors.

1529
00:51:30,700 --> 00:51:32,130
Let's just remind ourselves about

1530
00:51:32,130 --> 00:51:33,560
the rules for adding vectors.

1531
00:51:35,100 --> 00:51:37,800
There are three ways of thinking about adding vectors.

1532
00:51:38,500 --> 00:51:39,680
In the first way,

1533
00:51:39,680 --> 00:51:41,260
let's say A plus B.

1534
00:51:41,300 --> 00:51:42,100
A plus B.

1535
00:51:42,100 --> 00:51:42,640
A plus B.

1536
00:51:43,900 --> 00:51:44,340
A plus B.

1537
00:51:44,340 --> 00:51:45,800
We take A and we lay it out.

1538
00:51:47,420 --> 00:51:48,820
Here's one end of it,

1539
00:51:48,820 --> 00:51:49,640
the tail end of it.

1540
00:51:50,040 --> 00:51:51,780
Here's the arrow end of it.

1541
00:51:51,900 --> 00:51:54,320
Then we take B and we put the

1542
00:51:54,320 --> 00:51:56,740
tail of B at the head of A.

1543
00:51:58,740 --> 00:52:00,300
We draw a triangle.

1544
00:52:01,400 --> 00:52:03,760
The triangle has its third leg,

1545
00:52:03,760 --> 00:52:04,520
C,

1546
00:52:04,520 --> 00:52:06,660
which is the sum of A plus B.

1547
00:52:07,440 --> 00:52:09,320
It might be a degenerate triangle.

1548
00:52:09,540 --> 00:52:10,890
It might be that B is

1549
00:52:10,890 --> 00:52:12,240
along the same direction as A.

1550
00:52:12,240 --> 00:52:13,460
In which case,

1551
00:52:13,460 --> 00:52:15,540
C will also be along the same direction.

1552
00:52:15,640 --> 00:52:16,800
It'll look something like this.

1553
00:52:17,980 --> 00:52:18,840
In which case,

1554
00:52:18,840 --> 00:52:21,300
it's a kind of a degenerated triangle.

1555
00:52:21,800 --> 00:52:22,360
But still,

1556
00:52:22,360 --> 00:52:23,480
we'll just think of it as a triangle.

1557
00:52:24,400 --> 00:52:26,860
We can add vectors by this rule.

1558
00:52:29,460 --> 00:52:32,380
We can multiply vectors by numbers.

1559
00:52:34,140 --> 00:52:34,540
Oh,

1560
00:52:34,540 --> 00:52:35,540
before I do that,

1561
00:52:35,540 --> 00:52:36,600
let's just talk about the

1562
00:52:36,600 --> 00:52:37,660
two other ways of adding vectors.

1563
00:52:37,780 --> 00:52:38,300
They're trivial.

1564
00:52:39,399 --> 00:52:40,620
According to this rule,

1565
00:52:40,620 --> 00:52:41,420
it looks like it might

1566
00:52:41,420 --> 00:52:42,220
depend on the number of vectors.

1567
00:52:42,220 --> 00:52:43,540
It might depend on which one I lay down first.

1568
00:52:43,760 --> 00:52:44,780
But of course it doesn't.

1569
00:52:45,140 --> 00:52:47,080
You can choose a rule which

1570
00:52:47,080 --> 00:52:49,020
is symmetric between the two of them.

1571
00:52:49,160 --> 00:52:50,480
If this is A and this is B,

1572
00:52:50,480 --> 00:52:53,320
you put the tails of A and B down together.

1573
00:52:53,480 --> 00:52:54,560
You draw a parallelogram.

1574
00:52:55,720 --> 00:52:59,100
And you draw the diagonal of the parallelogram.

1575
00:52:59,240 --> 00:53:00,000
And that's called C.

1576
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:01,060
And in this form,

1577
00:53:01,060 --> 00:53:03,880
it's completely manifestly clear that it doesn't

1578
00:53:03,880 --> 00:53:05,120
matter whether you put A

1579
00:53:05,120 --> 00:53:06,360
down first or B down first.

1580
00:53:06,760 --> 00:53:07,860
So A plus B is

1581
00:53:07,860 --> 00:53:08,960
the same as B plus A.

1582
00:53:09,720 --> 00:53:10,120
Okay,

1583
00:53:10,120 --> 00:53:12,200
so that's vector addition.

1584
00:53:12,220 --> 00:53:17,300
You can multiply vectors by numbers,

1585
00:53:17,300 --> 00:53:18,800
either positive or negative.

1586
00:53:19,120 --> 00:53:20,840
Let's call this A.

1587
00:53:20,840 --> 00:53:23,020
We know exactly what that means.

1588
00:53:23,460 --> 00:53:28,720
We can multiply B by a number B.

1589
00:53:29,500 --> 00:53:30,400
What am I doing?

1590
00:53:30,560 --> 00:53:30,840
B.

1591
00:53:30,840 --> 00:53:34,720
And we can add them.

1592
00:53:34,780 --> 00:53:35,980
We know how to multiply by numbers.

1593
00:53:36,100 --> 00:53:36,820
We know how to add.

1594
00:53:37,040 --> 00:53:39,620
And that means we know how to

1595
00:53:39,620 --> 00:53:42,200
construct the vector A times vector B.

1596
00:53:42,220 --> 00:53:44,300
Vector A plus B times vector B.

1597
00:53:44,300 --> 00:53:45,780
We know exactly what that means.

1598
00:53:47,300 --> 00:53:49,340
The third way of adding

1599
00:53:49,340 --> 00:53:51,380
vectors is to use the components.

1600
00:53:52,380 --> 00:53:55,640
So if we have two vectors with components AX,

1601
00:53:55,640 --> 00:53:55,900
AY,

1602
00:53:55,900 --> 00:53:56,460
and AZ,

1603
00:53:56,460 --> 00:53:59,660
and BX,

1604
00:53:59,660 --> 00:53:59,880
BY,

1605
00:53:59,880 --> 00:54:00,740
and BZ,

1606
00:54:00,740 --> 00:54:05,780
then CX

1607
00:54:06,419 --> 00:54:09,060
is just equal to AX plus BX.

1608
00:54:10,580 --> 00:54:11,540
And likewise,

1609
00:54:11,540 --> 00:54:12,200
BX.

1610
00:54:12,880 --> 00:54:14,800
CY and CZ.

1611
00:54:15,560 --> 00:54:19,660
We could summarize this all by saying C sub I,

1612
00:54:19,660 --> 00:54:22,180
where I could be XY or Z or 1,

1613
00:54:22,180 --> 00:54:22,360
2,

1614
00:54:22,360 --> 00:54:22,700
or 3,

1615
00:54:22,800 --> 00:54:25,920
is equal to AI plus BI.

1616
00:54:26,780 --> 00:54:28,760
And that's an equivalent way,

1617
00:54:28,760 --> 00:54:30,400
a useful way,

1618
00:54:30,400 --> 00:54:31,260
to add vectors,

1619
00:54:31,260 --> 00:54:34,420
since often we specify the

1620
00:54:34,420 --> 00:54:37,940
vectors by their components.

1621
00:54:39,380 --> 00:54:40,140
All right.

1622
00:54:40,180 --> 00:54:41,300
If we can add vectors.

1623
00:54:41,540 --> 00:54:42,100
And...

1624
00:54:44,720 --> 00:54:47,900
Subtract vectors and multiply them by numbers,

1625
00:54:47,900 --> 00:54:50,460
the natural question is,

1626
00:54:50,460 --> 00:54:52,140
can we multiply vectors?

1627
00:54:52,820 --> 00:54:54,540
Can we divide vectors?

1628
00:54:54,760 --> 00:54:54,940
Well,

1629
00:54:54,940 --> 00:54:55,160
no,

1630
00:54:55,160 --> 00:54:56,480
we're not going to divide vectors.

1631
00:54:56,660 --> 00:55:01,700
The idea of vector division is not a well-defined idea.

1632
00:55:02,460 --> 00:55:06,390
But there are vector products.

1633
00:55:07,680 --> 00:55:09,960
There are two kinds of vector products.

1634
00:55:10,240 --> 00:55:10,900
Okay.

1635
00:55:11,600 --> 00:55:14,260
There are two distinct concepts of multiplying vectors.

1636
00:55:14,720 --> 00:55:15,780
In one of them,

1637
00:55:15,780 --> 00:55:17,100
when we multiply two vectors,

1638
00:55:17,100 --> 00:55:18,500
we don't get another vector.

1639
00:55:18,680 --> 00:55:20,220
We get a number.

1640
00:55:21,160 --> 00:55:22,660
A thing that's called a scalar.

1641
00:55:22,980 --> 00:55:25,140
And sometimes a number is just called a scalar.

1642
00:55:25,580 --> 00:55:28,230
So one definition of the product of

1643
00:55:28,230 --> 00:55:30,880
two vectors is called the dot product.

1644
00:55:31,140 --> 00:55:33,120
Let's talk about the dot product of two vectors.

1645
00:55:33,880 --> 00:55:35,520
A dot B.

1646
00:55:37,540 --> 00:55:40,480
A dot B is defined in the following way.

1647
00:55:40,520 --> 00:55:40,880
A dot B is defined in the following way.

1648
00:55:40,880 --> 00:55:42,080
You take A.

1649
00:55:43,920 --> 00:55:45,120
You take B.

1650
00:55:46,220 --> 00:55:49,400
And now you think of the component

1651
00:55:49,400 --> 00:55:52,580
of A along the axis of B.

1652
00:55:53,140 --> 00:55:54,240
What does that mean?

1653
00:55:57,320 --> 00:56:00,720
That means you drop a perpendicular from

1654
00:56:00,720 --> 00:56:04,120
the end of A to the axis,

1655
00:56:04,120 --> 00:56:05,280
not to the x-axis,

1656
00:56:05,280 --> 00:56:06,280
not to the y-axis,

1657
00:56:06,280 --> 00:56:07,300
not to the z-axis,

1658
00:56:07,300 --> 00:56:10,120
but to the axis defined by B.

1659
00:56:10,120 --> 00:56:12,260
So you drop a perpendicular.

1660
00:56:15,120 --> 00:56:18,160
And now you take the length of,

1661
00:56:18,160 --> 00:56:20,180
let's call this here,

1662
00:56:20,180 --> 00:56:23,180
A sub B,

1663
00:56:23,180 --> 00:56:26,060
the component of A along the B-axis.

1664
00:56:27,320 --> 00:56:31,450
You take the component of A along the B-axis and

1665
00:56:31,450 --> 00:56:35,580
you multiply it by the component of B along the B-axis.

1666
00:56:35,860 --> 00:56:38,240
What's the component of B along the B-axis?

1667
00:56:38,660 --> 00:56:39,300
A.

1668
00:56:39,300 --> 00:56:39,860
A.

1669
00:56:40,120 --> 00:56:41,040
It's the magnitude of B.

1670
00:56:41,880 --> 00:56:45,460
So you take the component of A along the B-axis,

1671
00:56:45,460 --> 00:56:47,240
you multiply it by the

1672
00:56:47,240 --> 00:56:49,020
component of B along the B-axis.

1673
00:56:49,880 --> 00:56:52,040
And that's called the dot product.

1674
00:56:52,180 --> 00:56:54,340
I'll write it out in a minute more definitely.

1675
00:56:54,740 --> 00:56:55,800
That's called the dot product.

1676
00:56:55,900 --> 00:56:57,120
But the way they defined it,

1677
00:56:57,120 --> 00:57:00,310
it looks like A dot B might

1678
00:57:00,310 --> 00:57:03,500
not be the same as B dot A.

1679
00:57:06,260 --> 00:57:07,160
After all,

1680
00:57:07,160 --> 00:57:08,630
the rule for B dot A was that the dot

1681
00:57:08,630 --> 00:57:10,100
product of A was the same as B dot A.

1682
00:57:10,100 --> 00:57:12,220
And that the value of A would be to drop

1683
00:57:12,220 --> 00:57:14,340
a perpendicular from B onto the axis defined by A,

1684
00:57:14,480 --> 00:57:15,500
which is a different thing,

1685
00:57:15,500 --> 00:57:17,440
and then multiply them together.

1686
00:57:18,040 --> 00:57:20,060
Is it obvious that A dot B

1687
00:57:20,060 --> 00:57:22,080
and B dot A are the same thing?

1688
00:57:22,460 --> 00:57:22,940
Well,

1689
00:57:22,940 --> 00:57:25,930
if we can write them in a manner

1690
00:57:25,930 --> 00:57:28,920
which is symmetric between the two of them,

1691
00:57:28,920 --> 00:57:30,860
then we'll know they're the same thing.

1692
00:57:31,100 --> 00:57:31,520
Okay,

1693
00:57:31,520 --> 00:57:33,480
so let's call this angle here theta.

1694
00:57:33,480 --> 00:57:33,580
theta.

1695
00:57:33,580 --> 00:57:38,820
The magnitude of A is the length of A,

1696
00:57:38,820 --> 00:57:40,640
the magnitude of B is the length of B.

1697
00:57:41,100 --> 00:57:44,660
What is the component of A along the B axis?

1698
00:57:44,660 --> 00:57:49,450
A sub B is equal

1699
00:57:49,450 --> 00:57:54,240
to the magnitude of A times

1700
00:57:54,240 --> 00:57:56,260
the cosine of the angle between them,

1701
00:57:56,260 --> 00:57:56,540
right?

1702
00:57:56,540 --> 00:57:57,980
What's called theta AB.

1703
00:57:57,980 --> 00:58:00,020
Theta is an angle

1704
00:58:00,020 --> 00:58:03,000
now and it's the angle between A and B.

1705
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:05,600
That's the component of A along the B axis.

1706
00:58:05,600 --> 00:58:07,000
We now

1707
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:08,590
multiply that by the magnitude of

1708
00:58:08,590 --> 00:58:10,180
B to get the dot product.

1709
00:58:10,180 --> 00:58:13,280
So the dot product is A dot

1710
00:58:13,280 --> 00:58:20,960
B and it's equal to AB cosine theta.

1711
00:58:20,960 --> 00:58:23,040
I won't bother writing theta AB.

1712
00:58:23,040 --> 00:58:29,400
The component of

1713
00:58:29,400 --> 00:58:29,700
A along the B axis is

1714
00:58:29,700 --> 00:58:30,000
the angle between A and B.

1715
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:30,000
So the dot product is A dot B and it's

1716
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:30,560
the length of A along the B axis.

1717
00:58:30,560 --> 00:58:33,520
That's this times the component of B along the B

1718
00:58:33,520 --> 00:58:33,800
axis,

1719
00:58:33,800 --> 00:58:35,300
which is just the magnitude of B.

1720
00:58:35,300 --> 00:58:36,520
It's AB,

1721
00:58:36,520 --> 00:58:38,940
magnitude of AB cosine of theta.

1722
00:58:38,940 --> 00:58:39,260
Now in

1723
00:58:39,260 --> 00:58:39,840
this form,

1724
00:58:39,840 --> 00:58:42,690
it's completely clear that it's completely

1725
00:58:42,690 --> 00:58:45,540
symmetric between A and B and it

1726
00:58:45,540 --> 00:58:48,460
doesn't matter in which order you multiply them together.

1727
00:58:48,460 --> 00:58:51,280
The cosine of the angle is

1728
00:58:51,280 --> 00:58:52,480
just the cosine of the angle.

1729
00:58:52,480 --> 00:58:55,360
Is A dot B always positive?

1730
00:58:55,360 --> 00:58:58,640
And under what circumstances,

1731
00:58:58,640 --> 00:58:59,100
if

1732
00:58:59,100 --> 00:58:59,320
not,

1733
00:58:59,320 --> 00:59:01,320
under what circumstances would it be negative?

1734
00:59:01,320 --> 00:59:06,580
If the cosine is negative.

1735
00:59:06,580 --> 00:59:07,340
When

1736
00:59:07,340 --> 00:59:08,220
is the cosine negative?

1737
00:59:08,220 --> 00:59:10,220
The cosine is negative if the

1738
00:59:10,220 --> 00:59:12,220
angle is bigger than 90 degrees.

1739
00:59:12,220 --> 00:59:13,320
So

1740
00:59:13,860 --> 00:59:15,280
that would be the situation,

1741
00:59:15,280 --> 00:59:16,160
for example,

1742
00:59:16,160 --> 00:59:20,220
where A was pointing like that.

1743
00:59:20,220 --> 00:59:22,860
Then the component

1744
00:59:22,860 --> 00:59:25,020
of A in the B direction would be negative.

1745
00:59:25,020 --> 00:59:28,740
If cosine of theta would be negative

1746
00:59:28,740 --> 00:59:32,460
for an angle bigger than 90 degrees,

1747
00:59:32,460 --> 00:59:38,900
the cosine is negative.

1748
00:59:40,180 --> 00:59:43,720
What about two perpendicular vectors?

1749
00:59:43,720 --> 00:59:46,880
Zero.

1750
00:59:46,880 --> 00:59:50,200
Cosine of theta is zero for 90 degrees.

1751
00:59:50,200 --> 00:59:54,900
So a diagnostic for deciding whether two vectors are

1752
00:59:55,020 --> 00:59:59,460
perpendicular or not is to calculate the dot product.

1753
00:59:59,460 --> 01:00:03,580
Now that can be useful.

1754
01:00:03,580 --> 01:00:03,860
And the

1755
01:00:03,860 --> 01:00:05,900
reason it can be useful is because we

1756
01:00:05,900 --> 01:00:07,940
can express the dot product in component form.

1757
01:00:09,200 --> 01:00:12,400
If we express the dot product in component form,

1758
01:00:12,400 --> 01:00:13,420
I won't prove this.

1759
01:00:13,420 --> 01:00:16,800
This is not hard

1760
01:00:16,800 --> 01:00:17,280
to prove,

1761
01:00:17,280 --> 01:00:21,900
that in terms of the components of the vectors,

1762
01:00:21,900 --> 01:00:25,000
this is equal to A over B

1763
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:32,180
AX BX plus AY BY plus AZ BZ.

1764
01:00:32,180 --> 01:00:35,580
In other words,

1765
01:00:35,580 --> 01:00:37,680
you multiply the components and you add.

1766
01:00:37,680 --> 01:00:38,960
That

1767
01:00:38,960 --> 01:00:40,220
can be easily proved,

1768
01:00:40,220 --> 01:00:42,420
little bit of trigonometry,

1769
01:00:42,420 --> 01:00:43,080
not much,

1770
01:00:43,080 --> 01:00:47,580
that this is equal to this over here.

1771
01:00:48,060 --> 01:00:48,840
Now that's nice.

1772
01:00:48,840 --> 01:00:51,380
Let me show you how you can use that.

1773
01:00:53,280 --> 01:00:53,900
Let's see,

1774
01:00:53,900 --> 01:00:54,620
do we really need that?

1775
01:00:55,220 --> 01:00:55,660
Well,

1776
01:00:55,660 --> 01:00:57,470
if I just were to

1777
01:00:57,470 --> 01:00:59,280
give you the components of A,

1778
01:00:59,280 --> 01:01:00,180
three numbers,

1779
01:01:00,180 --> 01:01:01,280
and the components of

1780
01:01:01,280 --> 01:01:01,460
B,

1781
01:01:01,460 --> 01:01:02,380
three numbers,

1782
01:01:02,380 --> 01:01:04,320
and ask you to compute

1783
01:01:04,320 --> 01:01:06,260
the angle between A and B,

1784
01:01:06,260 --> 01:01:07,600
your first reaction

1785
01:01:07,600 --> 01:01:09,300
might be to throw up your hands and say,

1786
01:01:09,300 --> 01:01:09,540
well,

1787
01:01:09,540 --> 01:01:10,080
I don't know,

1788
01:01:10,080 --> 01:01:11,400
get me a protractor and I'll

1789
01:01:11,400 --> 01:01:12,880
try to measure it.

1790
01:01:12,880 --> 01:01:14,820
But here's a tool now.

1791
01:01:14,820 --> 01:01:18,340
You calculate the dot product between them.

1792
01:01:19,520 --> 01:01:21,120
That gives you A dot B.

1793
01:01:22,060 --> 01:01:24,180
You can also calculate...

1794
01:01:24,180 --> 01:01:24,640
What is the

1795
01:01:24,640 --> 01:01:25,860
magnitude of A?

1796
01:01:28,300 --> 01:01:31,540
It is the dot product of A with itself.

1797
01:01:31,540 --> 01:01:33,820
Let's write A dot...oh,

1798
01:01:33,820 --> 01:01:34,140
sorry,

1799
01:01:34,140 --> 01:01:34,860
that's not quite right.

1800
01:01:35,100 --> 01:01:35,860
A dot A.

1801
01:01:35,860 --> 01:01:36,460
What is that?

1802
01:01:39,820 --> 01:01:42,140
That's just the square of the magnitude of A.

1803
01:01:42,140 --> 01:01:45,220
So that's A squared.

1804
01:01:45,220 --> 01:01:47,300
Likewise for B.

1805
01:01:47,300 --> 01:01:48,820
So,

1806
01:01:48,940 --> 01:01:51,820
you could calculate the magnitude of A,

1807
01:01:51,820 --> 01:01:53,500
or the square of it,

1808
01:01:53,500 --> 01:01:54,620
is AX squared plus A dot

1809
01:01:54,620 --> 01:01:55,760
AY squared plus AZ squared.

1810
01:01:55,760 --> 01:01:58,160
Likewise for the magnitude of B.

1811
01:01:58,160 --> 01:02:00,220
And then you would calculate

1812
01:02:00,220 --> 01:02:03,610
the angle between them by calculating the

1813
01:02:03,610 --> 01:02:07,000
dot product of the two of the vectors.

1814
01:02:07,000 --> 01:02:08,520
So

1815
01:02:08,520 --> 01:02:10,050
from the magnitude of each one of them

1816
01:02:10,050 --> 01:02:11,580
and the dot product of two of them,

1817
01:02:11,580 --> 01:02:12,260
you would

1818
01:02:12,260 --> 01:02:14,500
compute the cosine of the angle between them.

1819
01:02:15,060 --> 01:02:15,660
All right,

1820
01:02:15,660 --> 01:02:17,170
so that's a good trick if you

1821
01:02:17,170 --> 01:02:18,680
want to know the angle between two vectors.

1822
01:02:18,680 --> 01:02:21,100
Let's

1823
01:02:21,100 --> 01:02:22,960
prove the law of cosines.

1824
01:02:24,080 --> 01:02:24,600
Let's prove the law of cosines.

1825
01:02:24,600 --> 01:02:26,180
Let's prove the law of cosines.

1826
01:02:26,180 --> 01:02:27,760
This is a simple elementary thing.

1827
01:02:27,760 --> 01:02:29,500
Supposing we have

1828
01:02:29,500 --> 01:02:30,920
two vectors A and B,

1829
01:02:30,920 --> 01:02:33,770
and we want...think of it

1830
01:02:33,770 --> 01:02:36,620
as two sides of a triangle,

1831
01:02:36,620 --> 01:02:37,520
and we want

1832
01:02:37,520 --> 01:02:38,770
to compute the length of

1833
01:02:38,770 --> 01:02:40,020
the other side of the triangle.

1834
01:02:40,020 --> 01:02:41,820
So let's call that C.

1835
01:02:41,820 --> 01:02:43,340
C is equal

1836
01:02:43,340 --> 01:02:44,200
to A plus B.

1837
01:02:44,200 --> 01:02:46,980
How do we compute the length of C?

1838
01:02:46,980 --> 01:02:50,360
Let's just...C is equal to A plus B

1839
01:02:50,360 --> 01:02:50,780
squared,

1840
01:02:50,780 --> 01:02:54,580
or A plus B dotted with A.

1841
01:02:54,580 --> 01:02:55,200
A plus B.

1842
01:02:55,200 --> 01:02:58,820
The square of the length of a vector

1843
01:02:58,820 --> 01:03:02,440
is the dot product of the vector with itself.

1844
01:03:03,060 --> 01:03:05,340
So if the vector happens to be C,

1845
01:03:05,340 --> 01:03:07,020
this is C dot C,

1846
01:03:07,020 --> 01:03:10,600
that's the square of the length of

1847
01:03:10,600 --> 01:03:10,820
C.

1848
01:03:15,760 --> 01:03:16,800
Let's get...

1849
01:03:16,800 --> 01:03:17,500
Did I make a mistake?

1850
01:03:17,620 --> 01:03:18,160
A minus B.

1851
01:03:18,160 --> 01:03:18,160
Sorry.

1852
01:03:18,160 --> 01:03:19,580
A minus B.

1853
01:03:19,580 --> 01:03:20,560
A minus B.

1854
01:03:20,560 --> 01:03:20,980
Thank you.

1855
01:03:20,980 --> 01:03:22,600
A minus B.

1856
01:03:22,600 --> 01:03:24,560
C is A minus B.

1857
01:03:24,560 --> 01:03:25,840
It's not A plus B.

1858
01:03:25,840 --> 01:03:28,080
A plus B would be over here.

1859
01:03:28,080 --> 01:03:32,420
We could do it that way,

1860
01:03:32,420 --> 01:03:32,820
couldn't we?

1861
01:03:32,980 --> 01:03:34,020
But let's do it.

1862
01:03:34,020 --> 01:03:35,420
It's A minus B.

1863
01:03:35,420 --> 01:03:37,220
And you can work out very

1864
01:03:37,220 --> 01:03:39,020
quickly that this is A minus

1865
01:03:39,020 --> 01:03:39,240
B.

1866
01:03:39,240 --> 01:03:39,740
Do it yourself.

1867
01:03:40,520 --> 01:03:40,840
Okay.

1868
01:03:40,840 --> 01:03:41,920
So it's A minus B squared.

1869
01:03:41,920 --> 01:03:42,980
What is this equal to?

1870
01:03:42,980 --> 01:03:46,920
This is equal to A dot A plus B

1871
01:03:46,920 --> 01:03:51,980
dot B minus 2 A dot B.

1872
01:03:51,980 --> 01:03:53,740
Right?

1873
01:03:53,740 --> 01:03:54,280
Just...

1874
01:03:54,280 --> 01:03:55,440
Just multiplying them together.

1875
01:03:55,440 --> 01:03:57,700
And this is just the square of A.

1876
01:03:57,700 --> 01:03:59,680
This is A...magnitude

1877
01:03:59,680 --> 01:04:02,000
of A squared plus the magnitude of B squared.

1878
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:05,120
And this is minus twice the magnitude of A

1879
01:04:05,120 --> 01:04:07,050
times the magnitude of B times

1880
01:04:07,050 --> 01:04:08,980
cosine of the angle between them.

1881
01:04:08,980 --> 01:04:10,500
That's called the law

1882
01:04:10,500 --> 01:04:11,520
of cosines,

1883
01:04:11,520 --> 01:04:15,890
that the size of the third leg of

1884
01:04:15,890 --> 01:04:20,260
a triangle is given by the sums of the

1885
01:04:20,260 --> 01:04:22,260
squares minus twice the product of the

1886
01:04:22,260 --> 01:04:24,260
lengths times the cosine of the length.

1887
01:04:24,260 --> 01:04:24,800
Okay.

1888
01:04:24,800 --> 01:04:28,700
So that's vector addition,

1889
01:04:28,700 --> 01:04:29,600
vector multiplication,

1890
01:04:29,600 --> 01:04:31,320
vector subtraction,

1891
01:04:31,320 --> 01:04:33,140
even vector multiplication,

1892
01:04:33,440 --> 01:04:34,020
the dot product.

1893
01:04:34,020 --> 01:04:36,920
We'll worry about the cross product another time,

1894
01:04:36,920 --> 01:04:37,440
not today.

1895
01:04:43,180 --> 01:04:44,000
All right.

1896
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:44,200
Now,

1897
01:04:44,200 --> 01:04:46,340
more...not more important,

1898
01:04:46,340 --> 01:04:48,520
but more interestingly,

1899
01:04:48,520 --> 01:04:51,700
we have not only a

1900
01:04:52,480 --> 01:04:53,860
algebra of vectors.

1901
01:04:53,980 --> 01:04:54,240
Okay.

1902
01:04:54,260 --> 01:04:54,720
Which means adding,

1903
01:04:54,720 --> 01:04:55,960
subtracting,

1904
01:04:55,960 --> 01:04:56,440
and so forth.

1905
01:04:56,440 --> 01:04:57,820
Oh,

1906
01:04:57,820 --> 01:04:58,480
as I said,

1907
01:04:58,480 --> 01:05:00,340
there's no notion of division

1908
01:05:00,340 --> 01:05:01,260
of two vectors.

1909
01:05:01,260 --> 01:05:08,020
And notice that for the dot product,

1910
01:05:08,020 --> 01:05:10,560
the product of two vectors is not

1911
01:05:10,560 --> 01:05:11,100
a vector.

1912
01:05:11,100 --> 01:05:12,320
It's a number.

1913
01:05:12,320 --> 01:05:14,270
The cross product is another

1914
01:05:14,270 --> 01:05:16,220
matter that we'll come to another

1915
01:05:16,220 --> 01:05:16,540
time.

1916
01:05:17,300 --> 01:05:17,900
Okay.

1917
01:05:17,900 --> 01:05:18,360
Now,

1918
01:05:18,360 --> 01:05:24,240
let's talk for a moment about the...

1919
01:05:24,240 --> 01:05:24,860
First of all,

1920
01:05:24,860 --> 01:05:27,740
about a particular vector which

1921
01:05:27,740 --> 01:05:30,620
characterizes the position of a particle.

1922
01:05:33,700 --> 01:05:35,200
Here's the position of a particle.

1923
01:05:35,200 --> 01:05:35,440
Now,

1924
01:05:35,440 --> 01:05:36,400
think of it as a particle.

1925
01:05:36,400 --> 01:05:36,820
In fact,

1926
01:05:36,820 --> 01:05:37,000
we're going

1927
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:38,820
to allow it to move around in a little while.

1928
01:05:38,820 --> 01:05:44,820
And the origin is a particular special point

1929
01:05:44,820 --> 01:05:45,840
that we've picked out.

1930
01:05:45,840 --> 01:05:48,460
We do have to worry about

1931
01:05:48,460 --> 01:05:51,080
what happens if we change the origin,

1932
01:05:51,240 --> 01:05:52,380
but we're not going to do that today.

1933
01:05:53,080 --> 01:05:53,520
Okay.

1934
01:05:53,520 --> 01:05:54,400
And therefore,

1935
01:05:54,400 --> 01:05:56,800
the position of the particle defines a vector.

1936
01:05:56,800 --> 01:05:58,420
That vector is usually called

1937
01:05:58,420 --> 01:05:59,260
little r.

1938
01:05:59,260 --> 01:06:00,780
r,

1939
01:06:00,780 --> 01:06:01,360
I suppose,

1940
01:06:01,360 --> 01:06:02,480
